Can systemic risks be regulated?
MILAN – Over the past two years, the global economy has been hit head-on by financial instability and sudden changes in market dynamics.
Other events of this kind are likely to occur, because after the crisis, the global economy is imbalanced in many ways, particularly with regard to sovereign debt and the structure of global demand.
Systemic risks are the origin of most crises and pose a challenge for several reasons.
Firstly, they are not easy to detect safely and are even more difficult to prove.
Then, predicting the exact moment of the breaking point (when bubbles burst, when markets are paralyzed, and when there is no more credit available) is, and will likely remain, beyond our analytical capabilities.
Finally, crises are strongly nonlinear events that occur without warning signs.
The periodic manifestations of instability impose a high social cost on those who are least responsible for them.
If this pattern were to repeat itself, it could erode trust in financial markets and regulatory authorities, a loss of trust that could herald excessive regulations, state intervention, and a disengagement from globalization.
But the problem is even more serious.
The financial and economic crisis is transforming into a crisis of sovereign debt of advanced countries.
Economic and financial imbalances can translate into a dangerous fiscal imbalance, characterized by a deterioration of tax revenues and an increase in bailout expenses.
The International Monetary Fund estimates that up to 75 percent of the "fiscal packages" of advanced economies include non-discretionary counter-cyclical measures.
Undetected systemic imbalances and risks make fiscal policies that seem prudent not actually so.
For example, Spain did not have a fiscal deficit at the beginning of the crisis.
But its revenues and expenses were largely determined by a real estate bubble related to very high debt.
An extreme fiscal imbalance can also lead to a "growth trap" in which fiscal consolidation has such a negative effect on growth that it cancels itself out.
Greece is probably a typical example.
In the end, the only way out is to reset the value of liabilities through restructuring or inflation.
If systemic risks can trigger this kind of sequential imbalance in cascades, it is up to "sovereign" states to be aware of the danger, able to identify the appearance of a systemic risk, and take quick corrective measures.
New detailed legislative frameworks, focusing on capital requirements and leverage effects, transparency, ratings, and other sources of information, incentives, conflicts of interest, and limits on the size of financial institutions, consumer protection, and resolution mechanisms, will soon be adopted.
The hope is that these reforms will reduce the probability and severity of systemic risks.
However, this will in no way solve the problem of global imbalances and other factors contributing to and signaling instability.
In addition to and in complement of new legislative frameworks, a complete system of systemic risk surveillance is necessary.
However, some leading politicians and analysts believe that such a system, aimed at identifying and mitigating systemic risks, is futile.
The incomplete models of risk dynamics and a complex and permanently changing global financial system make risk detection, according to them, either impossible or so prone to error that this effort would be unproductive.
Asset bubbles are almost impossible to identify without error.
If the skeptics are right, we must then accept that we will periodically be in a situation of financial and fiscal instability without being able to predict it in advance.
We should then also accept a much more prudent fiscal policy than we thought necessary just three years ago.
In the field of statistics and decision-making under uncertainty, errors are inevitable.
There are two types of errors: one consists of rejecting a true proposal and the other is accepting a false proposal.
Let's call them RQV (rejected when true) and AQF (accepted when false).
The question can be posed in these terms: in the context of risk detection and response to systemic risks, which of these two types of errors has the highest probable cost?
Opponents of prudent surveillance of systemic risks have two different positions.
One of them is that the AQF error will not occur, because there is no reliable indicator of increasing potential instability.
Searching for such a sign is a waste of time.
Instability occurs instantly.
However, this position seems fallacious.
For example, during the 2008 crisis, some analysts issued warnings and some investors took note.
However, we must admit that these warnings were perhaps not sufficient to be irrefutable and they certainly did not predict the breaking point.
They were undoubtedly signs.
The second position is that there are indeed warning signs, but they are so unreliable that taking measures would do more harm than good.
This viewpoint implies that AQF has a higher probable cost than RQV, because there are many false positive elements and/or the remedy is worse than the disease.
There is no doubt that there are costs associated with the error AQF.
But RQV is also costly, as we have seen, so much so that the aggregate negative effect of a reaction to false positives (AQF) must be significant to be convincing.
I, for my part, am not convinced.
There may be a deeper trend at play.
Whether in business or investments, choices are constantly made in conditions of uncertainty, and errors are frequent.
The default position of policymakers in advanced countries seems to be that proactive and preemptive measures require a high level of certainty, linked to the deeply held belief that financial markets are stable and self-regulating.
If one thinks that market instability is rare, it is then reasonable to refrain from acting unless one has good reasons to do so.
But in light of past experiences, the idea that the global financial system is only exceptionally unstable or on a slippery slope is at least debatable.
Based on new theories and experiences, we might eventually conclude that policy responses to systemic risks are impossible to develop and that the cost of AQF errors is higher than the cost of RQV errors.
But we should at least try the experiment, and give responsibility for this to a new institution, or an existing institution, that has access to relevant information, possesses sharp analytical skills at both the financial and macroeconomic levels, and is relatively immune to conflicts of interest.
Its analysis should be made public and could thus influence perceptions of systemic risks and market behavior, thereby increasing the financial system's ability to regulate itself.
